def my_describe(df):
    print('='*40)
    print('We have', df.shape[0], 'rows, and', df.shape[1], 'columns.')
    print('='*40)
    desc = df.describe([], include='all', datetime_is_numeric=True).T.replace(np.nan,'-')
    desc['type'] = df.dtypes.astype('str')
    desc['count'] = desc['count'].astype('int')
    if len(df.select_dtypes('number').columns):
        desc = desc[['type', 'count', 'unique', 'top', 'freq', 'mean', 'std', 'min', '50%', 'max']]
    else:
        desc = desc[['type', 'count', 'unique', 'top', 'freq']]
    return desc.sort_values(['type', 'count'])

In [6]:
### change data types ###
df['start_time'] = df['start_time'].astype('datetime64')
df['birthyear'] = df['birthyear'].astype('int16')
df['tripduration'] = df['tripduration'].str.replace(',', '').astype('float64')/60 # in minutes
df['gender'] = df['gender'].astype('category')
df['usertype'] = df['usertype'].astype('category')

### add time related columns ###
df['year'] = df['start_time'].dt.year
df['month'] = df['start_time'].dt.month
df['month_name'] = df['start_time'].dt.month
df['day_num'] = df['start_time'].dt.dayofweek
df['day_of_week'] = df['start_time'].dt.dayofweek
df['hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour

### drop end time ###
del df['end_time']

### fix days of week ###
days = {0:'Mon', 1:'Tue', 2:'Wed', 3:'Thu', 4:'Fri', 5:'Sat', 6:'Sun'}
df['day_of_week'] = df['day_of_week'].apply(lambda x: days[x])
weekdays = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']
df['day_of_week'] = pd.Categorical(df['day_of_week'], categories=weekdays, ordered=True)

### fix month names ###
months = {1:'Jan', 2:'Feb', 3:'Mar', 4:'Apr', 5:'May', 6:'Jun', 7:'Jul',
          8:'Aug', 9:'Sep', 10:'Oct', 11:'Nov', 12:'Dec'}
df['month_name'] = df['month_name'].apply(lambda x: months[x])
month_ord = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun',
             'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
df['month_name'] = pd.Categorical(df['month_name'], categories=month_ord, ordered=True)

### add season ###
season = ['Winter','Spring','Summer','Fall']
seasons = dict(zip(range(1,13),
                   [season[(mon%12+3)//3-1] for mon in range(1,13)]))
df['season'] = df['month'].apply(lambda x: seasons[x]).astype('category')

### add age and age groups ###
df['age'] = 2019 - df['birthyear']
df = df[df['age'] >= 14]
df = df[df['age'] <= 80]
df['age_group'] = pd.cut(x=df['age'], bins=[0, 29, 39, 49, 59, np.inf],
                         labels=['<29', '30s', '40s', '50s', '60+'])

# Hexplot — sns.jointplot(kind = ‘hex’)

# Hexplot is one way of visualizing a bivariate correlation, especially when handling large datasets, because it splits the
# plotting window into several hexbins and then the number of observations which fall into each bin
# corresponds with a color to indicate density. A darker color hexbin means that there are more observations, or more density,
# within that region. The observation frequency bar graphs can be seen along the spines as an additional reference for
# information. We will use a hexplot to analyze how number of goals scored is related to number of shot attempts.

# Again, this graph can be somewhat inherent. As the great Wayne Gretzky/Michael Scott once said, “you miss 100% of the shots
# you don’t take”. We would believe that as shots increase, so do number of goals. The hexplot reiterates this notion.
# We see the darkest hexbin in the bottom right, as it is the most dense because scoring a goal in the NHL is no easy feat and
# the majority of players will be centered around this area. As we increase hexbins to the right and upwards, the color slowly
# begins to fade which indicates that there is a decreasing positive relationship between shot attempts and goals scored.

val = ['tripduration', 'str_dist', 'speed']
ats = ['(min)', '(km)', '(km/hr)']

for i in range(3):
    heat = pd.pivot_table(df, values=val[i],
                          index=df['start_time'].dt.to_period('M'),
                          columns=df['day_of_week'],
                          aggfunc='mean')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14,8))
    sns.heatmap(heat, cmap='RdBu_r', fmt='.2f',
                annot=True, annot_kws={'size':10}, ax=ax,
                cbar_kws={'label':val[i]+' mean in '+ats[i]});
    ax.set_title('mean of '+val[i]+' vs. day of week along dataset timeline', fontsize=15)
    ax.set_ylabel('timeline')
